Azure Cloud Concepts :
======================

High Availability : 
-------------------

> App --> VM ( OS Disk and Data Disk )  [ service level agreement ] ( if failure )
> App --> VM VM VM ( Availability set or Availability zone )
> Storage Accounts --> zone-redundant storage or Geo-redundant storage

Scalibility :
-------------

> We have virtual machine scale set service. which uses to provision or deprovision our VMs based on the demand.
> We don't need to worry about underlined storage of storage account. It automatically scales based on demand.

Disaster recovery :
-------------------

> We can protect our data in case of any disasters by using availability set, availability zones.
> For storage accounts, we need to use Geo-redundant storage.
> cost analysis : quick switch over from primary to secondary region, additional cost based on cost benfit analysis based on what will be loss for the down time of the application versus having that duplicate infrastructure is running on the secondary region.

Elasticity :
------------

> The ability to grow or shrink resources automatically as part of cloud platform
> Ex : for vm, we can resize the vm

Fault tolerance :
-----------------

> Suppose any fault ( error ) occurs for a high available application, it breaks our application. At this time fault tolerance is the ability to quickly revert back of your application.
> If fault occurs in a data center level, then your application will run from another availability zone.
> For Storage accounts, we have zone/geo redundant storage options.

Cloud Service Model :
---------------------

> IaaS : Ex : VM -> infra provided by cloud and managed by user. ( Admins )
> PaaS : Ex : Azure SQL Database -> underlined infrastructure and os is managed by azure and software can be managed by user. ( Developers )
> SaaS : Ex : Microsoft Office 365 -> Underlined infrastructure and the software is managed by azure. End user use the application ( End users )

Cloud Model types :
-------------------

> Public Cloud : Cloud can be used be any one.
> Private Cloud : Cloud can you used by particular organization.
> Hybrid Cloud : Based on requirement we can use public cloud and private cloud.

Economies of scale :
--------------------

> Basics : This is the ability to carry out taks more efficiently or at a lower-cost per unit when operating at a large scale.
> discounts : When the demand increases, cloud provides can then get hardware at discount prices.
> Benfit : This becomes a benfit to the customer wherein the discounts can be passed to the customer.
> service cost : If the number of customers increase the chances of services costs can go down.
> Captital Expenditure ( CapEx ) : This is when you pay money upfront [ one time investment ]( buying building, servers, storage, software liecences )
> Operational Expenditure ( OpEx ) : Ongoing money spent on services ( Human Resources, Maintenance, software support, data center costs - cooling )

Shared Responsibility Model :
-----------------------------

> Division of responsibility :
		> On-prem : Everything can be resposible for you.
		> IaaS : Physical hosts, network, data center has responsibility of cloud. Remaining things has responsibility of user.
		> PaaS : In addition with IaaS, Azure has shared responsibility in Identity and directory infrastructure, applications, network controls with user.
		> SaaS : User is reponsible for Information and data, devices, accounts and identities. Azure had shared responsibility with Identity and directory infrastructure.

Azure Traffic Manager Profile :
===============================

> It is a global service ( not specific to region ).This is a DNS-based traffic load balancer.
> You can distribute traffic to public facing applications across different azure regions.
> You can direct traffic based on different routing methods.
> Priority routing method : It routes the traffic of your web app running at particular region. If your web app is down, then traffic manager routes traffic to its duplicate copy of web app running at another region.
> Weighted traffic manager : Suppose your web app is running in different regions. It routes 50% of traffic to the both regions.
> Open Azure traffic manager profile > create > add endpoints > configure settings > Take DNS of the traffic manager profile and test it in the browser.

Azure Content Delivery Network ( Front Door and CDN profiles ) :
=======================================

> Helps to deliver content to users across the globe by placing content on physical nodes across the world.
> Suppose our web app is running on east-us and if users are trying to access the web app from the different regions, usually it requires access time to get that web app from one region to another region to the user. To avoid this access time, we can use azure cdn  service.
> By creating CDN Profile we can avoid access time. It is a global level endpoint.

workflow of the azure CDN service :
-----------------------------------

1. The user in the east us location makes a request to the CDN endpoint.
2. The CDN checks whether the Point of presence location closest to the user has the requirested file.
3. If not a request is made to the source to get the required file.
4. A server in the Point of presence location will then cache the required file.
5. The server will also send the file to the user.
6. subsequent users from the same location will now be served the file from the server in the point of presence location.

Azure DevOps services :
=======================

> uses to collaborate Dev and Ops teams ( plan,code,build,test,release,deploy, operate, monitor )
> Automation is a key aspect
> Adoption of the right tools
> Azure Devops services are : Azure Boards, Azure Pipelines, Azure Repos, Azure Test Plans, Azure Artifacts, Extensions Marketplace.
> Open Azure DevOps > create a organization > create a project > Advanced > git, agile
> Azure Boards : Used to manage agile flow of the project. it has boards, backlogs, sprints, queries and delivery plans etc.
> Azure Repos : This service is helpful manage your source code repositories such as git etc. we can set our own git respository to manage our source code.
> Azure pipelines :
	1. Build pipeline : We can build pipeline by setting up your github reposity and configure and review yaml file and run your job.
	2. Release pipeline : Releases > new pipeline > add artifacts > Add stages > save and run.
	
Azure DevTest Labs :
====================

> By using this service, we can setting up a dev test lab with vm's with required artifacts. 

Creating a Machine learning workspace :
=======================================

> create a Machine Learning service > along with this service it creates storage account, key vault, application insights, container registry services > Next Next Review and create.
> Launch studio 
> we can create our machine learning project on the canvas [ by drag and drop various steps to our project ]
> create a compute cluster and run your machine learning project on top of it.

Azure Congnitive services :
===========================

> Provides AI services in different categories such as speech, language, vision, decision, OpenAI service etc.

Azure Bot Service :
===================

> Using Bot SDK we can develop our own Bot service using any of the language [ c#, java, javascript or python ].
> download BotFrameworkEmulator from official source.
> install bot templates and reuse templates in your project to create your own Bot.

Azure Key Vault :
=================

> This service is uses to store our secrets, certificates, keys.

Azure Logic Apps :
==================

> This provides a cloud platform where you can create and run automated workflows.
> You don't need to well versed in code to implement there workflow.
> You can set trigger for the workflow.
> You can set various actions in the workflow and trigger the actions.

Azure IoT Lab :
===============

> This is a managed service that can be used as a central message hub for bi-directional communication between managed devices and an IoT application.
> The IoT hub supports communication both from the device to the cloud and from the cloud to the device.
> The IoT hub also gives a secure communication channel for devices to send data.
> Use case : Azure IoT service takes data from the IoT devices and forward to the Azure SQL database through the Azure Stream Analytics service.

Azure Batch Service :
=====================

> This service is used to run large-scale parallel and high performance computing batch jobs.
> This service manages the pool of VM's running your application.
> There is no additional cost for this service. You are only charged for the compute service.

Azure Active Directory :
========================

> It is an Identity provider.
> As part of the AD we can define multiple users and set permissions to the users.
> We can also define Application objects which can be map to the application and set permissions to the azure resources to that application.
> step1 : user authentication
> step2 : Authorizations ( Grant permission to access the resource )
> We can grant permissions using role based access control.
> The default user is linked to our subscription with administrator access.
> AD pricing : free, Office 365 apps, Premium P1, Premium P2
> Users are also called as identities.


creating a user in AD :
-----------------------

> open AD service > Users > New User > create user / invite user > provide info > create
> Click on the user > copy user principle name
> In another incognito window, we login to the azure portal using user principle name.

Role based access control :
---------------------------

> We can set permissions to the subscription level, all resources, resource groups, or to a particular azure resource.
> From the azure resource we can set permissions :
	> Open your azure service ( Ex : VM ) > open Access Control ( IAM ) > click on Add ( role assignment ) > choose required roles > assign to the users, groups or service principals > next > review and create.
	
Azure AD Groups :
-----------------	

> If we want users are part of any group, we can create groups and assign permissions to the groups as well.
> Open AD > Groups > New Group > name and add members > create.
> We can add and remove users from the group.
> nesting groups is not possible.
> If we delete the group, It will not affect on the User.
> We can assign permissions to any azure resource ( using IAM of resource ) from the group.

Multi-Factor Authentication :
-----------------------------

> To authenticate to the azure account, usually we require credentials. But, increase the security to the azure account we use multi factor authentication.
> It is a additional layer of security.
> Open AD > User > click on ... and select per-user MFA > select user and enable MFA.
> user required to register for the MFA code using using MS authenticator mobile app or phone.

Azure AD Premium Trail Licensing :
----------------------------------

> open AD > licenses > try/buy > Azure AD Premium P2 ( free trail 30 days with 100 licenses )
> If you want to continue to this service, upgrade to the paid version.
> Azure AD Premium P2 --> $9/month
> Azure AD Premium P1 --> $6/month

Conditional access policies :
-----------------------------

> open AD > ( applicable for Azure AD Premium P2 license) security > conditional access > new policy > name, assign to user or group or cloud app / actions, conditions, access control ( grant access ) > enable policy and create.

Passwordless Authentication options for Azure AD :
--------------------------------------------------

> Biometric mechanism
> MS Authenticator App

Azure AD - External IDentities :
--------------------------------

> We can create/invite external user from another organization ( different account ) as a contractor or contributor.
> Open AD > Users > New user > New external user > Invite
> We can assisn roles using IAM of azure resource to the External user.

Hybrid Environments - Identities :
----------------------------------

> Microsoft AD is manages users in the onpremesis server while azure AD manages users in the azure cloud subscription and manages ms apps ( 365 ).
> Azure AD connect is a service uses to synchronise users from onpremises environment to the cloud.
> Azure AD Domain services : This gives you the option of hosting the full version of Microsoft AD as a managed software on the cloud. You get the options of domain join, group policy, lightweight directory access protocol and Kerberos/NTLM authentication.

Microsoft Defender for Cloud :
------------------------------

> Using this service, we will get recommendations to secure our azure account.
> Using Secure score, we can analyse security level of our azure account.
> free and paid versions are available. paid version provides much more options to provide security to our azure account.
> We can also provide security to the resources deployed by other cloud providers such as aws, gcp.
> Under recommendations, we can see recommendations.
> Environment settings >click on your subscription > defender plans ( Here we can enable defender plan for certain services ( it will charge ).
> Your company is planning on using the Microsoft Defender for Cloud service. Can you view the regulatory compliance of your Azure resources in Azure Security Center? Yes


Microsoft Sentinel :
--------------------

> This service is used for security informaton ,event management, security orchestration, automation and response.
> vm ,azure activity log and Azure active directory sign-ins->log analytics workspace->Microsoft sentinel (enable) [ it collects data ,detects threats and respond and investigate threats ]
> create log analytics workspace > create Microsoft Sentinel and add the log analytics workspace 
> Open Microsoft Sentinel > open data connectors which collects data from azure and third party services > Using Analytics, we can detect threats by using default rules or we can define rules.


Azure DDoS (Distributed Denial of Service) Protection :
-------------------------------------------------------

> This service helps us to protect from DDoS attacks.
> DDoS is unwantedly increasing the traffic to your application by melicious users. They tries to down your application.
> DDoS attack will result performance issues of your application.


Azure Firewall :
----------------

> Has built-in high availability
> can deploy the azure firewall instance across two or more availabilityzones - 99.99% SLA
> You can also create network filtering rules - based on source and destination IP address. port and protocol.
> It is stateful in nature. so it understands what packets of data to allow.
> It has built-in treat intelligence -  here you can get alerts or deny traffic from / to malicious IP addresses and domains.
> when we are launching vm we need to create a AzureFirewallSubnet with in a vnet.
> create Azure fire wall serivce
> open firewall manager > policy > we can set rules ( DNAT, Network, Application )
> It costs per hour.

Concept of zero trust :
-----------------------

> When user want to communicate with azure cloud resources from on-premises servers. There are some Foundation principles :
	1. Verify explicitly -  Ensure to always authenticate and authorize users.
	2. Use least access privileges wherever possible.
	3. Assume breach -  Understand your surface area when it comes to threats, look at threat intelligence.
> Secure Identities, Secure Endpoints, Secure Applications,Secure Data.

Defence of Depth :
------------------

> We can be secure our data by deep

> Security levels :
	Physical security
	Identity and access
	Perimeter
	Network
	Compute
	Application
	Data
	
